-- EXECUTION SUMMARY
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
--
-- Total frames: 20 (0-19)
-- ⊢∘ iterations: 1 (converged immediately — soft-count' = 0 after first pass)
-- ⊢∘ max was 3, used 1 — decomposition was effective on first iteration
-- ⊢⊢ spawn-sub-decomposers: fired once, spawned 2 refiner cells (accumulate)
-- ⊢⊢ spawn-crystallizers: fired once, spawned 10 check cells (replace)
-- File-scope ⊨? active but never triggered (no oracle failures)
-- Total cells spawned dynamically: 12 (2 refiners + 10 checks)
-- Total cells in final graph: 17 (5 original + 12 spawned)
--
-- Cells evaluated:
--   api-artifact, root-oracle (pass-through)
--   decompose (soft, LLM, ⊢∘-managed)
--   spawn-sub-decomposers (⊢⊢ spawner)
--   refiner-0, refiner-1 (soft, LLM)
--   collect-results (soft, LLM)
--   spawn-crystallizers (⊢⊢ spawner)
--   check-0 through check-9 (⊢= crystallized, deterministic)
--   assemble-hierarchy (soft, LLM)
--   verify-coverage (⊢= crystallized, deterministic)
--
-- LLM calls: 5 (decompose, refiner-0, refiner-1, collect-results, assemble-hierarchy)
-- Deterministic evals: 11 (10 check cells + verify-coverage)
-- Spawner evals: 2 (spawn-sub-decomposers, spawn-crystallizers)
-- Pass-through: 2 (api-artifact, root-oracle)
--
-- Oracle results: ALL PASS (0 failures across all cells)
--
-- Key observations:
--
-- ⊢= Observation 1: ⊢∘ convergence in 1 iteration validates decomposition quality
--   The refine-loop exited after a single iteration because both refiners
--   produced exclusively "structural" and "deterministic" sub-oracles — no
--   soft residue. This validates the program's design: if the initial
--   decomposition is well-chosen (4 clear dimensions of "good API design"),
--   one level of refinement suffices. The ⊢∘ max-3 safety net was never
--   needed. In a real deployment with vaguer root oracles (e.g., "the
--   system is well-designed"), multiple iterations would be expected.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 2: crystallization ratio reveals the fusion boundary
--   Of 20 frames, 11 were deterministic (⊢=) and 5 required LLM evaluation.
--   The program's purpose — converting soft oracles to hard checks — IS the
--   crystallization process made explicit. After the refine-loop completes,
--   every remaining evaluation is deterministic. The LLM is used exclusively
--   at the creative frontier (decomposition, refinement, assembly) while
--   verification (checks 0-9, verify-coverage) runs without semantic computation.
--   This is Cell's fundamental thesis: the hard core grows as the soft frontier
--   recedes.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 3: wildcard deps enable structural decoupling of spawners
--   collect-results uses refiner-*→refined-oracles to gather outputs from
--   however many refiners were spawned. assemble-hierarchy uses check-*→holds
--   to gather all leaf check results. Neither cell knows how many upstream
--   cells exist at parse time — the wildcard resolves dynamically against the
--   graph. Under v0.2, this is formally specified: the wildcard re-resolves at
--   each ready-set computation, and the cell becomes ready when ALL matching
--   cells have frozen the referenced field. This is the key mechanism that
--   makes recursive spawning composable.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 4: spawner modes (accumulate vs replace) serve distinct roles
--   spawn-sub-decomposers uses accumulate because refiners from iteration N
--   should coexist with refiners from iteration N+1 (each targets different
--   soft oracles). spawn-crystallizers uses replace because the leaf check set
--   should reflect the FINAL oracle list, not a union of intermediate states.
--   In this trace, the distinction is moot (only 1 ⊢∘ iteration), but in a
--   multi-iteration run, accumulate would build up a growing set of refiners
--   while replace would discard stale leaf checks and rebuild from scratch.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 5: ⊢= expression language enforces honest crystallization
--   Each check cell's ⊢= body uses only v0.2 primitives: contains(), and, ←.
--   No semantic judgment masquerading as deterministic code. The expression
--   "contains(errors, '400') and contains(errors, 'details[]')" is genuinely
--   deterministic — a classical runtime can evaluate it without an LLM. Under
--   R16, the check template used pseudo-code like "<deterministic check of
--   oracle-text against artifact>" which was a placeholder for undefined
--   semantics. v0.2's expression language forces each check to be honest about
--   what it can actually compute.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 6: the hierarchy tree is a proof certificate
--   assemble-hierarchy's output is effectively a proof tree: each leaf carries
--   evidence (the specific artifact value checked), each internal node carries
--   a classification (structural/deterministic), and the root carries the
--   original vague oracle. The tree structure IS the decomposition proof —
--   it shows exactly how "the API design is good" was reduced to 10
--   independently verifiable facts, each grounded in a specific artifact field.
--   This is the proof-carrying computation pattern applied to oracle chains:
--   the LLM produces the proof (decomposition), deterministic code verifies it
--   (leaf checks), and the tree assembles both into a certificate.
